## Aristotle argues in his metaphysics

Essence is substance and the account of this is definition which is identified by genus and differentia ; they are prior to species ; divided into two ; matter representing potentiality of genus and form representing actuality of differentia ;

For example “round bronze“
He argues these are not constituted by two separate forms ; instead
Here bronze is potential matter genus
And round is actual form differentia ;& both part refers to different components of definiendum ;

Later he presents three approaches to definition

a.disclose the formal cause of definiendum ;
b.


Ghazali says everything which cannot be known immediately can only be known from the sake of definition ;( tusi agrees )

A complete definition generates complete knowledge of definiendum ; farabi ; while incomplete definition generates accidental properties ;

Razi; a proper definition conveys its (def) essence and mahiyyah;conceptualizing its quiddity ; it can be complete or incomplete ; complete fully captures definiendums genus , differentia ; no hadd is valid without them ;


ITs first argument;

Thus it is said: If “definition” is the statement uttered by the definer, then either one has already come to know the definiendum (almahdud) by way of some other definition, or one has come to know it without any definition at all. If the former is the case, then discussion of this second definition is no different from the discussion of the first—leading to a circularity (dawr) or an infinite regress (tasalsul) in the causes (al-'ilal) and reasons, both of which the rational consensus deems impossible. If, however, one came to know it without a definition, then their original premise—namely, that “it cannot be known except by definition”—is thereby invalidated [24, p. 49; emphasis is mine].

Which is basically regress of definitions ; definitions require further definition for their explanation ; if not then other options to scape this like Aristotle is stating the words used in hadds are simple;non definable ; this means one can comprehend something other than definition which contradicts their epistemology ;

He also argues no one has ever established a sound definition; such as

Rational Animal or Sun as Large Celestial Body ;

Again ; IT argues human can perceive and comprehend by hiss ; such as taste color and what constitutes them without needing any definitions ; (sextus empiricus made similar arguments )

One can comprehend RED without knowing its wavelength and if its next to orange or not ;

... It may be said, “They [the philosophers] themselves acknowledge that some conceptions are self-evident (badihiyyah) and therefore require no definition ... In that case, one should reply: Determining whether a given piece of knowledge is “self-evident” or “theoretical” (nazari) falls under relative, comparative matters—just like a “proposition” (qadiyah) can be either certain (yaqiniyah) or merely conjectural (zanniyah) [24, p. 55; emphasis is mine]

He argues that even if some philosophers say some concepts are self evident to avoid regress ; there’s no distinct way to determine whether some concepts is self evident or which is need of definition ;

IT further makes arguments such as ;

For any definiens x ; it is the case that the hearer either knows its actual definition;or they dont ;

If former then x brings nothing since it doesn’t add anything to their knowledge;or if thats latter then ;there’s no way to verify whether x can generate knowledge or its a declarative statement;

IT argues one cannot check the truth of definiendum only consulting definition itself which is neutral and mere declarative proposition ;


IT s metaphysical criticism ;

He states that classification of properties such as essential and accidental is problematic; ph say essential predicate is internal to reality and accidental is external to it ;

Accidental predicates can be further divided as separable aka arad and inseparable aka lazim ;

Such as standing ;

Btw inseparable accidents are also further divided into 2 🙏;

Concomitant of existence; or concomitant of quiddity; former follows from the existence from the quiddity; such as shadow of horse which follows the existence but not quiddity;
Latter follows quiddity ;such as like evenness of number 2;

Now for IT; quiddity is meant to answer what is it?? Which is a mental category; to him ; no quiddity can have stable existence in extramental substances; if we approach the question by mental or nature ; so he basically rejects quiddity has stable truth extramentally ;

He further argues that the misguidance of ph, is within their observation ; how can a thing be observed prior to its actual existence?

He is mainly critiquing more of Peripatetics who were influenced by avicenna rather than aristotle ;since his position is more of qualified form of realism ; for him ; pure quiddity is neither mental nor platonic ;it exists only when form and matters are attached to it ; IT Objects saying there are only two modes of existence ; in mind and in reality (wujudi) ; further to prove his point; if quiddity refers to complete concept which is stable and extramental ; then its not possible to conceive it without essential properties which is false ;

Now if it is said that numbers are either odd or even ;not as distinct description ;but rather something as known number itself without any mediation ; or one cannot know them vua mediation such as one knows one is half of two ;

so whether any attribute is apprehended immediately or through intermediaries ; which pertains the capacity of human cognition; not other than that ;
the former is epistemic while later is ontological ; confusion stems from the usage of language;

Even if we were to assume ; we that there is an isomorphism between cognition of predicates and quiddity; still it’s contingent upon ; the subjects cognitive ability and prior knowledge of the subject; from that IT argues that the distinction philosophers present between quiddity and its existence collapses ;

ghazali made similar critiques ; arguing that identification of nearest genus is not always obvious ; a mujtahid could classify wine as impermissible entity whereas nearest genus mentally would be drinkn ;


Difference between Essential & Concomitant to Quiddity

Ph say predicates divided into ;

essential ; internal to quiddity ; constitutive of mahiyyah ;

concomitant (lazim) ; external to quiddity ; yet necessarily follows from it ;

Example ;

Four ;

Essential ; successor of 3 ; predecessor of 5 ;

Concomitant ; evenness ; divisibility by 2 ;

Distinction tested through conceivability ;

If p essential ; impossible to conceive Q without p ;

If p concomitant ; Q conceivable without p ;

IT rejects conceivability test ;

One may conceive “four” without reflecting whether it is even ; just as one may conceive “human” without reflecting upon rationality or animality ;

If ph reply ; that’s incomplete conception ;

IT ; same applies to four ; incomplete conception doesn’t prove ontological distinction ; only incomplete cognition ;

Thus ;

Differences in what one regards as essential ; follow differences in cognitive ability ; familiarity ; education ; not differences in extra-mental reality ;

Therefore ;

Essential vs concomitant ; relative to cognizer ; not stable metaphysical categories ;

IT first criticism ;

Ph arbitrarily privilege essential predicates over concomitant ones ;

No demonstration that rationality is metaphysically prior to laughter ;

Rather ;

Historical training ; linguistic habits ; pedagogical convention ;

People become accustomed to Aristotelian classifications ; then mistake conceptual habit for reality ;

Which is basically ;

Conceptual taxonomy mistaken for ontology ;

Second criticism ;

Ph say ;

Essential predicates constitute quiddity ;

Therefore ;

Parts of quiddity prior to whole ; both mentally and externally ;

Since whole composed from constituent parts ;

IT objects ;

Sequential speech ≠ sequential reality ; When describing human ; Sentient ; Growing ; Voluntary motion ; Speaking ;

These predicates uttered one after another ;

Language forces temporal sequence ;

Reality doesn’t ;

Priority belongs only to discourse ; not existence ;

Thus ;

Composition exists in thought ; language ; analysis ;

Not necessarily within extra-mental being ;

Hence distinction collapses ;

Quiddity ;
Essential predicates ;
Concomitant predicates ;

Reduce to three linguistic relations ;

Correspondence (mutabaqah) ;

Implication (tadammun) ;

Entailment (iltizam) ;

Rather than metaphysical structures ;
Basically ;
Ph read ontology from grammar ;
IT says grammar reflects cognition ; not reality ;

Razi’s similar criticism

Either quiddity defined ; By itself ; He Circular ; By internal predicates ; Analytically identical ; still circular ; By external predicates ; Only relational definitions ; regress ; Thus ; None establish genuine hadd ;


Was IT Nominalist?

Many classify IT as nominalist ;

Reason ;

Rejects separate quiddities ;
Rejects universals existing prior to particulars ;
Rejects quiddity existing independently of existence ;

But author argues ;

Not sufficient for nominalism ;

Nominalism requires positive theory of universals ;

Like Ockham ;

Universals = mental fiction ; or mental act ;

IT never develops such theory ; only dismantles Aristotelian account ;

Although appeals to sense perception ;
Accepts revelation ;
Testimony ;
Tawatur ;
Intuition ;
Multiple epistemic sources ;

Thus not British-style empiricism ;
Neither conventionalist ;
Although definitions depend partly on convention ;

IT explicitly rejects ;
Truth changes when conventions change ;
Scientific realities remain constant despite changing terminology ;

Therefore ;

Convention alone cannot ground knowledge ;

He can be classified as Pragmatic ;

Meaning determined through ;Context ; Speaker intention ; Usage ; Communicative function ; Natural regularities ; Sense experience ;

Not through discovering metaphysical essences ;

Which is basically ;

IT isn’t saying ;

'Universals are merely names.'

Nor ;

'Only particulars exist.'

Rather ;

He rejects that Aristotelian definitions mirror objective essences ;

Definitions function primarily as tools for ;

Naming ;
Differentiating ;
Referring ;
Communicating ;

Whether they capture an essence depends on context ; not on genus–differentia alone ;
